The Dowkerâ€“Thistlethwaite notation, also known as DT Code or simply Thistlethwaite notation, is an algorithm for finding and cataloguing all prime alternating links up to 10 crossings using finite fields. It was invented by Dennis Sullivan and further developed by John Milnor (and hence named after them) but independently discovered by Hugh Morton. The original proof involved some heavy algebraic topology, which has been replaced with combinatorics. The method uses skein theory to calculate the Jones polynomial of a link from its diagram; it then checks if this polynomial vanishes at the primitive nth roots of unity to determine whether the link is prime. If so, it calculates another invariant, the signature function, and adds that to the list. This approach can be used to construct all prime alternating links with fewer than ten crossings.
